"Hi Eleanor How are you?"
"Hi there XX. I'm doing well thanks! I hope your week has been going well too. How has everything been since we last spoke?"

I told him I speak with you on a regular basis and how much it helps. He's prescribed me lexapro to see if helps but I've been researching it and the side affects scare me"

"I'm sorry to hear that you've been struggling with your anxiety XX- sounds like a rough week. It is good that you went in to see your doctor about it. Yes these medications often do come with side effects... it sounds like this must be your first time taking antidepressants? What are the side effects in particular that worry you?"

"Yeah just struggling with the XXe stuff and there's a bit going on with the boss at work which hasn't helped. I'm feeling more down about my weight gain and don't want these pills to make it worse. Coma, confusion, convulsions, heart racing. I already get the heart race when I feel anxious, it makes me feel very uncomfortable and the other side affects scare the heck out of me. Not my first time being on antidepressants though, I was on diazepam when I was 22 I think it was due to the abuse etc I was getting from my ex, that continued till I was 25 but stopped taking them long before I left because I had the kids"

"Ah I see XX. Yes reading about those side effects can be quite frightening and it's definitely something to be aware of when starting any new medication. However, these are pXXably some of the more extreme side effects and aren't as likely to occur- I think our minds have the tendency to catastrophize with these things. A lot of my clients take Lexapro without any significant or debilitating side effects, and it works well for them. If you are willing to give it a try, you can always stop if you feel it is not working for you and ask your GP for a different medication. There can be some trial and error involved in finding the right medication for you, but it can make a big difference when you do find something that works for you. What are your thoughts? Would you like us to talk more about what's happening with your boss?"

"I know you're right, those symptoms just scare me more because I always think, if something happens to me who's going to take care of the kids. So it's a bit off putting I guess. "I underXXd your worry XX. Even if you know logically it is safe, it is normal to have some worry at the back of your mind. I am glad that you are willing to give it a go and hopefully you have another appointment with your doctor in a few weeks to review the medication. Your boss sounds like a really difficult person XX, and I can imagine that this would make the office environment quite tense and uncomfortable at times. I can also see how this would increase your anxiety and fear of making mistakes- which must be hard as I know you are still new and learning on your job. Is this what has contributed to those panic attacks?"

The fires around the place have contributed as well because for a few days there they felt like they were too close for comfort so the kids and I have now got packed bags in the car and are prepared to leave at any given time."

"Oh no, I imagine the risk posed by those fires must add to the stress and pressure too. It is good that you and the family have prepared for the possibility of evacuation XX. It must be difficult to function with that concern at the back of your mind all the time too... it is no wonder your anxiety has been getting on top of you. Sometimes having a plan of action for such events can help you to feel more in control, so here is a link for you to read through that might help with your planning/preparation: https://www.qfes.qld.gov.au/fireescape/index.html 

It is a positive thing that other people seem to be happy with your work, and better still that you are seeing improvements within yourself XX! Perhaps as you grow in confidence and adjust to the office environment/culture, your boss's behaviour will start to phase you less. However, are there people that you can talk to about this when you are struggling with her behaviour? Even just for a little support, even if they can't change anything?"

"Oh thank you very much for the link. Well I'm hoping that her behaviour won't phase me as much especially if this medication starts to help as well. I don't even want to go to the Christmas party because of her and because it's so far away from the kids. No not really anyone around, even though my daughter is only 14, she lets me bounce a few things off her when I get home from work as she seems to know the second I get home if I've had a bad day."

"It's really nice that your daughter can support you like that XX! Hopefully as time goes you will begin to form a bit of a support system at work too. You are pXXably not the only one who finds your boss's behaviour to be difficult. Sometimes just knowing that other people feel the XXe as you do and you are all in it together can be a big help. It sounds like you are experiencing some bumps in the road- which is frustrating but normal- but overall it looks like you are still heading in the right direction with things XX, and I think it's important to acknowledge what a good job you are doing. We are unfortunately out of time for our appointment today XX, but how are you feeling about what we've discussed today?"

"Yeah my daughter has been great. No I'm definitely not, one girl quit last week and the other one had a meeting with someone yesterday and told them that she is ready to walk too and that if things kept going I would pXXably be leaving as well. So some of us are in the XXe boat. Yes, that's true, I still lack acknowledging when I do a good job but I'm learning. I feel much better thank you Eleanor."
"I'm glad to hear you are feeling better XX :) Would you like to book in another appointment for a fortnight again?"
"Yes please. XXe time?"
"Sure XX, I'll book that in for you now. In the mean time, please take care and I hope you and your family stay safe! We'll talk again in 2 weeks. Have a good night! Regards, Eleanor"
